<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10076c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10076c">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10076c"> 76(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">D</font> reads own demise</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">On sait l&apos;histoire de cet esclave du roi Pausanias, s&apos;apercevant que les messagers envoy&eacute;s par son ma&icirc;tre au grand roi ne revenaient jamais, et qui, envoy&eacute; &agrave; son tour, pouss&eacute; par le soup&ccedil;on et la peur, <mark>viole les d&eacute;p&ecirc;ches, y trouve l&apos;ordre de le faire p&eacute;rir</mark> &agrave; son arriv&eacute;e en Perse, et court r&eacute;v&eacute;ler au s&eacute;nat de Sparte la trahison du roi. <font color="green">[There is a famous story of a slave of King Pausanias who noticed that the messengers sent by his master to the great king never returned. When it was his turn to be sent, filled with suspicion and fear, he unsealed the dispatches and found the order to have him executed upon his arrival in Persia. And so he ran to the Spartan senate to reveal the King&apos;s treason.]</font> <small> Arthur de Rothschild, <a name="ARHD" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ARHD"><cite title="source">Histoire de la poste</cite></a> (1876) 22-3</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c01036f" href="c01all.htm#c01036f">VI.C.01:036(f)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
